<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="176" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1070,827,879]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Etymology: The specific epithet (Latin, adjective: curved) refers to the shape of the ventral process of the aedeagus in lateral view.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="176" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1071,896,949]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
Description: Body length 
<quantity box="[549,681,896,918]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.25" metricValueMax="5.3" metricValueMin="5.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" unit="mm" value="5.25" valueMax="5.3" valueMin="5.2">5.2-5.3 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 2.9-3.0 mm. Externally similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[377,468,928,949]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rectus">
<emphasis box="[377,468,928,949]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">R. rectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but distinguished as follows:
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1028,966,988]" box="[163,1028,966,988]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[230,291,966,988]" captionStart="Figs 8-12" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1060,1080]" captionTargetBox="[163,1046,197,1029]" captionTargetId="figure-210@6.[163,1098,197,1033]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 8-12: Rugilus curvatus nov.sp.: (8) forebody; (9) male sternite VII; (10) male sternite VIII; (11) aedeagus in lateral view; (12) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9-12: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507311/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) 1.06-1.08 times as broad as long; punctation less extensively confluent.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1070,1004,1088]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
♂: sternite VII (
<figureCitation box="[327,388,1004,1026]" captionStart="Figs 8-12" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1060,1080]" captionTargetBox="[163,1046,197,1029]" captionTargetId="figure-210@6.[163,1098,197,1033]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 8-12: Rugilus curvatus nov.sp.: (8) forebody; (9) male sternite VII; (10) male sternite VIII; (11) aedeagus in lateral view; (12) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9-12: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507311/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) not distinctly modified; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[786,859,1004,1026]" captionStart="Figs 8-12" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1060,1080]" captionTargetBox="[163,1046,197,1029]" captionTargetId="figure-210@6.[163,1098,197,1033]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 8-12: Rugilus curvatus nov.sp.: (8) forebody; (9) male sternite VII; (10) male sternite VIII; (11) aedeagus in lateral view; (12) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9-12: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507311/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) with not very deep, broadly V-shaped posterior excision; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[685,803,1035,1057]" captionStart="Figs 8-12" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1060,1080]" captionTargetBox="[163,1046,197,1029]" captionTargetId="figure-210@6.[163,1098,197,1033]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 8-12: Rugilus curvatus nov.sp.: (8) forebody; (9) male sternite VII; (10) male sternite VIII; (11) aedeagus in lateral view; (12) aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 8: 1.0 mm; 9-12: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507311/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Figs 11-12</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[824,921,1035,1057]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" unit="mm" value="0.65">0.65 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process strongly curved in lateral view, apically acute in ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="176" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1071,1105,1403]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
Comparative notes: As can be inferred from the similar external and male sexual characters, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" box="[353,470,1136,1157]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvatus">
<emphasis box="[353,470,1136,1157]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">R. curvatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely allied to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="COIFFAIT" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[677,860,1135,1157]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadridentatus">
<emphasis box="[677,860,1135,1157]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">R. quadridentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingRegion box="[876,987,1135,1157]" country="Nepal" name="Dhawalagiri" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Dhaulagiri</collectingRegion>
) and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Annapurna)" baseAuthorityName="Annapurna" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rectus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">R. rectus</emphasis>
(Annapurna)
</taxonomicName>
. From the former, it is distinguished by the absence of a median posterior excision of the male sternite VII, the different shape of the posterior excision of the male sternite VIII, and by the differently shaped ventral process of the aedeagus. From the latter, it differs by the much shallower posterior excision of the male sternite VIII and by the much shorter and distinctly curved ventral process of the aedeagus. For additional characters separating it from 
<taxonomicName box="[613,713,1320,1341]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rectus">
<emphasis box="[613,713,1320,1341]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">R. rectus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see the description above. For illustrations of the male sexual characters of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="COIFFAIT" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[639,823,1350,1372]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadridentatus">
<emphasis box="[639,823,1350,1372]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">R. quadridentatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<figureCitation box="[875,938,1350,1372]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="4.[163,203,1098,1118]" captionTargetBox="[171,1067,199,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-251@4.[162,1069,197,1082]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-7: Rugilus rectus nov.sp. (1-6) and R. quadridentatus (COIFFAIT) (7): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3, 7) male sternite VII; (4) male sternite VIII; (5) aedeagus in lateral view; (6) ventral process of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 3-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4507309" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4507309/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING V" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" pagination="115 - 190" refId="ref11068" refString="ASSING V. (2012 a): The Rugilus species of the Palaearctic and Oriental regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde A, Neue Serie 5: 115 - 190." type="journal article" year="2012">ASSING (2012a)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="176" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1070,1420,1503]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">
Distribution and natural history The 
<typeStatus box="[841,877,1420,1441]" pageId="5" pageNumber="176">type</typeStatus>
specimens were found in two localities in the southern Annapurna range, some 
<quantity box="[815,913,1450,1472]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" unit="km" value="17.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="15.0">15-20 km</quantity>
to the north of Pokhara, at altitudes of 2400 and 
<quantity box="[503,582,1481,1503]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="176" unit="m" value="2600.0">2600 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
